tweet: It is recommended for men to consider seeing a genetics counselor for a consultation. If a man tests positive for a defective gene (most commonly either BRCA1 or BRCA2) that can lead to a future diagnosis of breast cancer and his children have a 50% chance of carrying the gene.

tweet: Up to 40% of all male breast cancer cases may be due to BRCA2 mutations.  This means men who get breast cancer are more likely to have an inherited gene mutation than women who get breast cancer.  pic.twitter.com/lLG80KPDw2
